{"title_page": "Chris Boyle", "text_new": "{{for|the Scottish footballer|Chris Boyle (footballer)}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name                = Dr Chris Boyle\n| fullname            = Christopher Boyle\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|8|11}}\n| birth_place         = [[Glasgow, Scotland]]\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         =\n| otheroccupation     = Academic, Researcher, Author\n| years1              =2010&ndash;\n| years2              =\n| years3              =\n| years4              =\n| league1             =[[A-League]]\n| league2             =[[SPFL]]\n| league3             =\n| league4             =\n| role1               = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| role2               = [Academic]\n| internationalyears1 =\n| confederation1      =\n| internationalrole1  =\n}}\n'''Dr. Chris Boyle''' (born 11 August 1972 in [[Glasgow, Scotland]]) is an Associate Professor in Psychology and Inclusive Education at the University of Exeter. He has previously been an [[association football]] [[referee (association football)|Referee]] who refereed in the Australian [[A-League]] and the Scottish Premiership.  Dr Boyle is a qualified psychologist working in the UK and in Australia. Dr. Boyle has written extensively on subjects of psychology and inclusive education. He has edited and authored over 30 publications (some can be downloaded for free [https://une-au.academia.edu/ChristopherBoyle here]). Dr. Boyle's five book publications can be viewed here:\n\n*Allen, K.A., & Boyle, C. (Eds). (2018). Pathways to Belonging Contemporary Research in School Belonging[https://brill.com/view/title/39413.]\n*Zhang, Z., Chan, P. W. K., & Boyle, C. (Eds.) (2014). [https://www.sensepublishers.com/catalogs/bookseries/other-books/equality-in-education-fairness-and-inclusion/ Equality in education: Fairness and inclusion. Rotterdam: Sense Publishers.]\n*Boyle, C., & Gamble, N. (2014). [http://www.oup.com.au/titles/higher_ed/psychology/9780195523102 Ethical practice in applied psychology. Melbourne: Oxford University Press.]\n*Boyle, C.  (Ed.) (2013). [https://www.novapublishers.com/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=42045&osCsid=bf2b2b9a1361dd34273efea914b4c210 Student Learning: Improving Practice. New York: Nova Publishers.]\n*Boyle, C., & Topping, K. (Eds.) (2012). [http://www.mcgraw-hill.co.uk/html/0335244688.html What works in inclusion? London: Open University Press].\n\nHe is currently Editor of the Australian Psychological Society's journal ''[http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayJournal?jid=EDP The Australian Educational and Developmental Psychologist] which is published biannually by Cambridge University Press.\n\n==History==\nBoyle has officiated matches in both the [[Scottish Premier League]], [[Scottish Football League First Division]] and [[Scottish Football League Second Division]]  making him one of the most experienced referee's in the [[A-League]]. He has also officiated a [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] game. He made headlines in his debut match of his [[A-League]] career when he officiated the game between [[Melbourne Victory]] and [[North Queensland Fury]] at [[AAMI Park]]. During the game, he awarded three penalties (two to Melbourne, one to North Queensland), and handed out two [[Penalty card#Red card|red cards]] to North Queensland players [[Chris Grossman]] and [[Eric Akoto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-league.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=34854|title=Nine-man Fury claim point|date=22 August 2010|publisher=A-League|accessdate=23 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225204843/http://a-league.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=34854|archivedate=25 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBoyle has previously worked as a secondary school teacher and as an educational psychologist in the UK. He has also lectured on the professional training programme for educational psychologists at the [[University of Dundee]], UK and in the subject areas of child development and psychology with the [[Open University]], UK. He has completed his PhD at the University of Dundee in the area of inclusion in secondary schools and teacher perceptions of inclusion which both form the main components of his current research interests.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\n==Books Published==\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ultimatealeague.com/referee_detail.php?referee_id=28 Ultimate A-League profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyle, Chris}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:A-League referees]]\n[[Category:Scottish football referees]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Scottish footballer|Chris Boyle (footballer)}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name                = Dr Chris Boyle\n| fullname            = Christopher Boyle\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|8|11}}\n| birth_place         = [[Glasgow, Scotland]]\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         =\n| otheroccupation     = Academic, Researcher, Author\n| years1              =2010&ndash;\n| years2              =\n| years3              =\n| years4              =\n| league1             =[[A-League]]\n| league2             =[[SPFL]]\n| league3             =\n| league4             =\n| role1               = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| role2               = \n| internationalyears1 =\n| confederation1      =\n| internationalrole1  =\n}}\n'''Dr. Chris Boyle''' (born 11 August 1972 in [[Glasgow, Scotland]]) is an Associate Professor in Psychology and Inclusive Education at the University of Exeter. He has previously been an [[association football]] [[referee (association football)|Referee]] who refereed in the Australian [[A-League]] and the Scottish Premiership.  Dr Boyle is a qualified psychologist working in the UK and in Australia. Dr. Boyle has written extensively on subjects of psychology and inclusive education. He has edited and authored over 30 publications (some can be downloaded for free [https://une-au.academia.edu/ChristopherBoyle here]). Dr. Boyle's five book publications can be viewed here:\n\n*Allen, K.A., & Boyle, C. (Eds). (2018). Pathways to Belonging Contemporary Research in School Belonging[https://brill.com/view/title/39413.]\n*Zhang, Z., Chan, P. W. K., & Boyle, C. (Eds.) (2014). [https://www.sensepublishers.com/catalogs/bookseries/other-books/equality-in-education-fairness-and-inclusion/ Equality in education: Fairness and inclusion. Rotterdam: Sense Publishers.]\n*Boyle, C., & Gamble, N. (2014). [http://www.oup.com.au/titles/higher_ed/psychology/9780195523102 Ethical practice in applied psychology. Melbourne: Oxford University Press.]\n*Boyle, C.  (Ed.) (2013). [https://www.novapublishers.com/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=42045&osCsid=bf2b2b9a1361dd34273efea914b4c210 Student Learning: Improving Practice. New York: Nova Publishers.]\n*Boyle, C., & Topping, K. (Eds.) (2012). [http://www.mcgraw-hill.co.uk/html/0335244688.html What works in inclusion? London: Open University Press].\n\nHe is currently Editor of the Australian Psychological Society's journal ''[http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayJournal?jid=EDP The Australian Educational and Developmental Psychologist] which is published biannually by Cambridge University Press.\n\n==History==\nBoyle has officiated matches in both the [[Scottish Premier League]], [[Scottish Football League First Division]] and [[Scottish Football League Second Division]]  making him one of the most experienced referee's in the [[A-League]]. He has also officiated a [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] game. He made headlines in his debut match of his [[A-League]] career when he officiated the game between [[Melbourne Victory]] and [[North Queensland Fury]] at [[AAMI Park]]. During the game, he awarded three penalties (two to Melbourne, one to North Queensland), and handed out two [[Penalty card#Red card|red cards]] to North Queensland players [[Chris Grossman]] and [[Eric Akoto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a-league.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=34854|title=Nine-man Fury claim point|date=22 August 2010|publisher=A-League|accessdate=23 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225204843/http://a-league.com.au/default.aspx?s=newsdisplay&id=34854|archivedate=25 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBoyle has previously worked as a secondary school teacher and as an educational psychologist in the UK. He has also lectured on the professional training programme for educational psychologists at the [[University of Dundee]], UK and in the subject areas of child development and psychology with the [[Open University]], UK. He has completed his PhD at the University of Dundee in the area of inclusion in secondary schools and teacher perceptions of inclusion which both form the main components of his current research interests.{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ultimatealeague.com/referee_detail.php?referee_id=28 Ultimate A-League profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyle, Chris}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:A-League referees]]\n[[Category:Scottish football referees]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Edpsych1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Boyle"}
